{"title":"What are Behavioural Biases?","markdown":{"yaml":{"title":"","page-layout":"full","toc":false,"listing":{"id":"biases-listing","contents":"biases","type":"grid","sort":"title asc","grid-columns":4,"image-height":"180px","fields":["image","title","description"],"page-size":999,"exclude":{"filename":["availability-heuristic.qmd","choices.qmd","frame-dependence.qmd","heuristics.qmd","mental-accounting.qmd","preference-reversals.qmd","representativeness.qmd","social.qmd"]}}},"headingText":"What are Behavioural Biases?","containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n\n```{=html}\n<section class=\"hero-section\">\n  <h1>The Effect of Behavioural Biases on Financial Decisions</h1>\n  <p class=\"subtitle\">A collection of cognitive biases and their influence on financial decision-making</p>\n\n  <!-- Cloned Quarto search widget, centered in the hero -->\n  <div class=\"hero-search\">\n    <div id=\"quarto-search\" class=\"type-overlay\" title=\"Search\"></div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"hero-tags\">\n    <a class=\"hero-tag\" href=\"biases/heuristics.qmd\">Heuristics and Judgemental Biases</a>\n    <a class=\"hero-tag\" href=\"biases/choices.qmd\">Choices: Framing and References</a>\n    <a class=\"hero-tag\" href=\"biases/social.qmd\">Social Factors</a>\n    <a class=\"hero-tag\" href=\"biases.qmd\">All Biases</a>\n  </div>\n</section>\n```\n\n\nBehavioural biases try to explain our tendency to reason in certain ways that can lead to systematic errors or deviations from a standard of rationality or good judgment in thinking or reasoning. In the financial setting, consequently, they aim to explain why consumers and investors make decisions that oppose the [standard model of rational choice](https://web.stanford.edu/~jdlevin/Econ%20202/Choice%20Theory.pdf), which states that when presented with a set of options, individuals choose the option that maximizes their expected utility.\n\nThis site serves as an anthology of {{< var n_biases >}} biases across three major categories, in line with the taxonomy proposed by [David Peon and Manel Antelo](https://hemeroteca.unad.edu.co/index.php/revista-estrategica-organizacio/article/view/4963/4705), including some examples from daily life for each.\n\n---\n\n## Browse by Category\n\n```{=html}\n<div class=\"bias-grid\">\n  <a class=\"bias-card\" href=\"biases/heuristics.qmd\">\n    <h3>Heuristics and Judgemental Biases</h3>\n    <p>Heuristics are mental \"rules of thumb\" used to simplify complex decision-making, distorting risk assessment and probability judgement.</p>\n  </a>\n  <a class=\"bias-card\" href=\"biases/choices.qmd\">\n    <h3>Choices: Framing and References</h3>\n    <p>How options are presented (framed) changes what we choose. Frame dependence, context effects, mental accounting, and preference reversals.</p>\n  </a>\n  <a class=\"bias-card\" href=\"biases/social.qmd\">\n    <h3>Social Factors</h3>\n    <p>Cultural and social factors affect our decision-making, leading to conformity, groupthink and herd mentality.</p>\n  </a>\n</div>\n```\n---\n\n## All Biases\n\n::: {#examples-listing}\n:::\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":"\n\n```{=html}\n<section class=\"hero-section\">\n  <h1>The Effect of Behavioural Biases on Financial Decisions</h1>\n  <p class=\"subtitle\">A collection of cognitive biases and their influence on financial decision-making</p>\n\n  <!-- Cloned Quarto search widget, centered in the hero -->\n  <div class=\"hero-search\">\n    <div id=\"quarto-search\" class=\"type-overlay\" title=\"Search\"></div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"hero-tags\">\n    <a class=\"hero-tag\" href=\"biases/heuristics.qmd\">Heuristics and Judgemental Biases</a>\n    <a class=\"hero-tag\" href=\"biases/choices.qmd\">Choices: Framing and References</a>\n    <a class=\"hero-tag\" href=\"biases/social.qmd\">Social Factors</a>\n    <a class=\"hero-tag\" href=\"biases.qmd\">All Biases</a>\n  </div>\n</section>\n```\n\n## What are Behavioural Biases?\n\nBehavioural biases try to explain our tendency to reason in certain ways that can lead to systematic errors or deviations from a standard of rationality or good judgment in thinking or reasoning. In the financial setting, consequently, they aim to explain why consumers and investors make decisions that oppose the [standard model of rational choice](https://web.stanford.edu/~jdlevin/Econ%20202/Choice%20Theory.pdf), which states that when presented with a set of options, individuals choose the option that maximizes their expected utility.\n\nThis site serves as an anthology of {{< var n_biases >}} biases across three major categories, in line with the taxonomy proposed by [David Peon and Manel Antelo](https://hemeroteca.unad.edu.co/index.php/revista-estrategica-organizacio/article/view/4963/4705), including some examples from daily life for each.\n\n---\n\n## Browse by Category\n\n```{=html}\n<div class=\"bias-grid\">\n  <a class=\"bias-card\" href=\"biases/heuristics.qmd\">\n    <h3>Heuristics and Judgemental Biases</h3>\n    <p>Heuristics are mental \"rules of thumb\" used to simplify complex decision-making, distorting risk assessment and probability judgement.</p>\n  </a>\n  <a class=\"bias-card\" href=\"biases/choices.qmd\">\n    <h3>Choices: Framing and References</h3>\n    <p>How options are presented (framed) changes what we choose. Frame dependence, context effects, mental accounting, and preference reversals.</p>\n  </a>\n  <a class=\"bias-card\" href=\"biases/social.qmd\">\n    <h3>Social Factors</h3>\n    <p>Cultural and social factors affect our decision-making, leading to conformity, groupthink and herd mentality.</p>\n  </a>\n</div>\n```\n---\n\n## All Biases\n\n::: {#examples-listing}\n:::\n"},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":false,"echo":true,"output":true,"warning":true,"include":true,"keep-md":f